===Adjective===
{{en-adj|-}}

# {{&lit|very|well|lang=en}}
#: ''I'm feeling '''very well''' today.''

===Adverb===
{{en-adv}}

# {{&lit|very|well|lang=en}}
#: {{ux|en|He managed the company '''very well'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|He understood '''very well''' that there might be difficulties.}}
#* {{RQ:WBsnt IvryGtP}}
#*: Thus, when he drew up instructions in lawyer language, he expressed the important words by an initial, a medial, or a final consonant, and made scratches for all the words between; his clerks, however, understood him '''very well'''.
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} {{non-gloss definition|Used to weaken the effect of certain [[modal verb]]s.}}
#: {{ux|en|It may '''very well''' rain this afternoon.}}
#: {{ux|en|I can't '''very well''' talk to you and concentrate on sanding this at the same time.}}

====Usage notes====
* {{sense|used to weaken the effect of modal verbs}} The improbability introduced by {{m|en|may}} is weaker in {{m|en||It may very well rain}} than in {{m|en||It may rain}}. Likewise, the impossibility meant by {{m|en|can't}} is weaker in {{m|en||I can't very well talk}} than in {{m|en||I can't talk}}.

===Interjection===
{{en-interj}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic|formal}} Indicating [[acceptance]], often with [[resignation]] or [[acquiescence]], of a statement or situation.
#: A: ''I don't want to go today.''
#: B: '''''Very well'''. Let's go tomorrow, then.''
# {{lb|en|naval}} A standard response by a superior to a report or confirmation.
#: Conning officer: "Rudder amidships."
#: Helmsman: "Rudder amidships aye! Rudder now amidships."
#: Conning officer: "Very well."

